

## 1️⃣lscpu – CPU Architecture Summary

Description: Shows high-level CPU info in a human-readable format.

Basic command:
lscpu


Output includes:
 Architecture (x86_64, arm64)
 CPU op-mode (32/64-bit)
 CPU(s) (total cores)
 Thread(s) per core
 Core(s) per socket
 Socket(s)
 Vendor ID
 Model name
 CPU MHz
 Cache size
 Flags (vmx, sse, avx)

Common options:

| Option | Description                                    |
| ------ | ---------------------------------------------- |
|-p   | Show in parsable format (good for scripts) |
|-e   | Show extended CPU info                     |
|-s   | Show summary                               |
|-x   | Show all extended info in key=value format |

Examples:
lscpu
lscpu -p      # script-friendly comma-separated output
lscpu -e      # extended info including core ID, socket ID


---

## 2️⃣cat /proc/cpuinfo – Detailed CPU Info

Description: Reads CPU info directly from the kernel.

Command:
cat /proc/cpuinfo


Output includes:
 Processor number
 Vendor ID
 CPU family
 Model name
 Stepping
 CPU MHz
 Cache size
 Flags (sse, avx, vmx)
 Physical ID / Core ID

Common use cases:

Count number of CPUs:
cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep -c processor

List CPU models:
cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep "model name" | uniq

View CPU flags:
cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep flags | uniq


---

## 3️⃣nproc – Number of CPU cores

Description: Prints the number of processing units available (logical cores).

Command:
nproc

Options:

| Option  | Description                                          |
| ------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
|--all | Show total CPU cores, ignoring affinity restrictions |

Examples:
nproc
nproc --all


Use case: Useful in scripts or CI/CD pipelines to parallelize jobs:
make -j$(nproc)


---

## 4️⃣top – Real-Time CPU Usage

Description: Interactive command showing CPU/memory usage per process.

Command:
top


Useful keys intop:

| Key | Action                      |
| --- | --------------------------- |
|1 | Show per-CPU usage          |
|P | Sort processes by CPU usage |
|M | Sort by memory usage        |
|k | Kill a process by PID       |
|r | Renice (change priority)    |
|q | Quit                        |

Options:

| Option         | Description                         |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------- |
|-d <seconds> | Set refresh delay, e.g.,top -d 3 |
|-p <pid>     | Monitor specific PID                |
|-u <user>    | Show processes of a specific user   |

Example:


top -d 2          # Refresh every 2 seconds
top -u root       # Show root processes only
top -p 1234       # Monitor PID 1234


---

## 5️⃣htop – Interactive CPU Monitor

Description: Advanced, colorful, interactive alternative totop. Needs installation.

Install:
sudo yum install htop      # RHEL/CentOS
sudo apt install htop      # Ubuntu/Debian


Command:
htop


Features:
 Per-core CPU bars
 Tree view of processes
 Kill/renice processes
 Search/filter processes
 Shows memory, swap, CPU usage, load averages

Options:
| Option         | Description                   |
| -------------- | ----------------------------- |
|-d <seconds> | Delay between refreshes       |
|-u <user>    | Show processes of a user only |
|-p <pid>     | Monitor specific PID(s)       |

Example:
htop -u root      # Show root user processes
htop -p 1234      # Monitor a specific PID


---

## 6️⃣mpstat – Per-CPU Usage Statistics
Description: Reports CPU usage per processor (requiressysstat package).

Install:
sudo yum install sysstat
sudo apt install sysstat


Command:
mpstat


Options:
| Option               | Description                                    |
| -------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
|-P <CPU>           | Report for a specific CPU (0,1, orALL) |
|-u                 | Show CPU utilization (user/system/idle/iowait) |
|<interval> <count> | Repeat every interval seconds, count times     |

Examples:
mpstat -P ALL 2 5     # Show all CPUs every 2 sec, 5 times
mpstat -P 0           # Show only CPU 0 stats
mpstat 1 3            # Report for all CPUs every 1 sec, 3 times


Output Columns:
%usr → time spent in user space
%sys → system/kernel time
%iowait → time waiting for I/O
%idle → idle time

---

## 7️⃣sar -u – CPU Usage History

Description: Shows historical CPU usage. Part ofsysstat package.

Enable collection (RHEL/CentOS):


sudo systemctl enable --now sysstat


Command:
sar -u


Options:
| Option               | Description                                        |
| -------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
|<interval> <count> | Show CPU stats every interval seconds, count times |
|-P <CPU>           | Show per-CPU stats (ALL or CPU number)           |
|-f <file>          | Read from a different sar data file                |

Examples:
sar -u 1 5        # CPU usage every 1 sec, 5 times
sar -P ALL 2 3    # Per-CPU usage, every 2 sec, 3 times
sar -u -f /var/log/sa/sa28  # Read historical file


Output Columns:
%usr → user CPU
%sys → system CPU
%iowait → waiting for I/O
%idle → idle time


